Curtis C. Reusser, the President and CEO of Esterline Technologies Corporation (ESL), Interviews with The Wall Street TranscriptHomeMailFlickrTumblrNewsSportsFinanceCelebrityAnswersGroupsMobileMoreTry Yahoo Finance on Firefox »YahooSearchSearchSign inU.S. Markets close in 6 hrs 21 minsS&P 5002,470.75-4.67 (-0.19%)Dow 3021,781.33-15.22 (-0.07%)Nasdaq6,355.21-26.97 (-0.42%)Curtis C. Reusser, the President and CEO of Esterline Technologies Corporation (ESL), Interviews with The Wall Street TranscriptWall Street TranscriptMay 27, 2014ReblogShareTweetShare67 WALL STREET, New York - May 27, 2014 - The Wall Street Transcript has just published its Industrial Equipment, Aerospace and Defense Report offering a timely review of the sector to serious investors and industry executives. This special feature contains expert industry commentary through in-depth interviews with public company CEOs and Equity Analysts. The full issue is available by calling (212) 952-7433 or via The Wall Street Transcript Online.Topics covered: Capital Equipment Technology Investing - Growth Opportunities in Data Security - Professional Security Equipment - Emerging Markets Penetration - Heightened M&A Activity - Future Growth and Market Share Gains - Increased Commercial Aircraft Production Rate - Aircraft Manufacturing Supply ChainCompanies include: Esterline Technologies Corp. (ESL) and many more.In the following excerpt from the Industrial Equipment, Aerospace and Defense Report, the President and CEO of Esterline Technologies Corporation (ESL) discusses company strategy and the outlook for this vital industry:TWST: How the business breaks down today, would you expect that to continue in the future, or is there any one area you are putting more focus on or that seems more promising?Mr. Reusser: If you look back at our recent history, we have traditionally had more of an equal split between defense and commercial aerospace. There have been two phenomena going on there. We made investments in new platforms or programs, such as Boeing's 787 aircraft. As you know, that program and others were a little bit slow to take off, but now we're really starting to see momentum build on the revenue side, and that is tending to increase the size of our commercial business.On the defense side, pressure on the U.S. and international defense budgets has caused contraction in that market. Those factors have tended to keep our organic sales fairly flat, but we see the defense side bottoming out, and with the advent of the JSF, increasing activity for the A400M and the P-8 - which we have very good placement on - starting to pick up steam, we should start to see some positive signs in that market. I think the commercial and defense mix will stay skewed a little bit more toward commercial for the time being, but defense is still a core piece of our business and should show promise going forward.The other thing of interest in our business is this 20% of revenue that exists in adjacent markets. There are three or four areas here where we see opportunity for double-digit growth. The interface controls for the medical business is growing at a very nice pace, and that's a good market for us. Another is gaming; we make human-machine interfacing button panels, and controls for slot machines and other regulated gaming devices. That market is growing pretty fast, especially in Asia, and we are well-positioned to capture business in that niche with our technology and product brands. A third strong adjacent market is nuclear, primarily in Europe. We do both connectors as well as containment and insulation systems for new builds and upgrades of existing nuclear reactors, specifically in the U.K. and elsewhere in Europe.So between those adjacent markets, we expect they will grow relatively rapidly which could make them a larger piece of our overall business if they perform as we expect they will. It's a nice business fit for us because they are typically servicing highly regulated markets, like aerospace and defense; they are typically dealing with harsh environments; they are generally highly engineered, specialized products; and they utilize the same supply chain, so it's an effective way to be able to capture some additional growth without having to get too far from our core technologies.TWST: What do you consider to be highlights of the company's performance since you started with Esterline?For more of this interview and many others visit the Wall Street Transcript - a unique service for investors and industry researchers - providing fresh commentary and insight through verbatim interviews with CEOs, portfolio managers and research analysts. This special issue is available by calling (212) 952-7433 or via The Wall Street Transcript Online.ReblogShareTweetShareRecently ViewedYour list is empty.What to Read NextConsumers, businesses lift U.S. economic growth in second quarterReutersEngineer Finds Pattern; Makes Millions in StocksMoney MorningSponsoredTrump’s unwitting legacy could be universal health coverageYahoo FinanceSean Hannity responds to claim he ran up a $42,000 tab at Trump's hotel after flying in a 70-year-old lobster from MaineBusiness InsiderXbox Live Games With Gold for August 2017InvestorPlaceDiscover it: 4.8 out of 5 avg. by 24K+ customersDiscover CardSponsoredTwitter is only famous now because of President Trump: NYSE traderYahoo Finance VideoInvestors yawn as US economic growth rebounds in the second quarter; Amazon fallsYahoo FinanceRepublicans warn Trump: No confirmation hearing for a Sessions replacement, and no recess appointment eitherBusiness Insider$20 Bitcoin Jackpot Could Explode By July 28Agora FinancialSponsoredExxon profit nearly doubles, but falls short of expectationsReutersStarbucks CEO: The Amazon-Whole Foods deal shows where retail is goingYahoo FinanceBoeing: Capitulation Time Againbarrons.comZuckerberg Wife's Ambitious Secret Finally ExposedUNewz.MeSponsoredAmazon could be the first trillion dollar company: NYSE 